    f.
        i? Positive vs negative checks
            When the receiver receives the data, it sends a copy of the data it has received back to the sender. The sender receives this copy. If this copy of the data is different to what the sender sent out, then there has been an error either in the initial transmission or during the transmission of the echo. If there is no error, the sender acknowledges the echo; otherwise, it reports this to the receiver.
        ii.
            Because prior to transmission, an algorithm such as SHA-256 is used to calculate a value based on the data. This algorithm always outputs the same value for the same input data. When the data is received, the value is calculated again using the same algorithm. The first calculated value is sent along with the data, so the receiver can compare the two values. If the values differ, then the receiver knows that either the transmitted checksum is wrong, or there is an error in the data. In either case, an error has occured.
    g.
        i.
            To prevent malicious actors from obtaining the contents of the email, which may contain sensitive information.
        ii.
            They both use secrets to produce a ciphertext
        iii.
            In symmetric encryption, one key is shared between both parties, whereas in asymmetric encryption, each party has their own private key and public key, making four keys in total vs one
            In symmetric encryption, the same key is used for encrypting and decrypting, whereas in asymmetric encryption, different keys are used for encrypting and decrypting.
